  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Unapproved structures are significantly more common in Brisbane than most people expect. Decades of owner-builder work, renovations done without permits, and secondary dwellings added informally mean that a large proportion of inner-east properties have at least one structure that was never approved by Brisbane City Council. Decks and outdoor entertainment areas, garden sheds converted to studios, carports and garages, and granny flats added to accommodate ageing parents are the most frequent examples.</p>

      <p>For most of the life of a property, unapproved structures sit quietly without issue. When you decide to sell, they become a live consideration. How you address them, or whether you address them at all, has real consequences for your disclosure obligations, your buyer pool, and your sale price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How common are unapproved structures in Brisbane's inner east?</h2>
      <p>Brisbane's inner-east suburbs contain a high proportion of older homes, many of which were built or substantially modified before council approval processes were as rigorous as they are today. Queenslanders and post-war homes particularly in suburbs like Camp Hill, Norman Park, Morningside, Bulimba, and Carina are frequently found to have had decks added, lower levels enclosed, and outbuildings constructed over the decades without permits being pulled.</p>

      <p>Brisbane City Council does not maintain a publicly searchable register of unapproved work in the same way some other councils do, but a building history search or a pre-sale building inspection by an experienced inspector will often surface structures that do not appear in the approved plans. Buyers conducting their own due diligence, particularly those working with experienced conveyancers, will often identify unapproved structures during the contract period through council records requests and building inspections.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Unapproved versus non-compliant: an important distinction</h2>
      <p>These two terms are often used interchangeably but they mean different things, and the distinction has real implications for what you can do about the structure before selling.</p>

      <p>An unapproved structure is one that was built without obtaining the required building approval from Brisbane City Council before construction commenced. The work may have been done competently and to a standard that would have passed inspection at the time. It simply was not submitted for approval. In many cases, these structures can be retrospectively approved if the work meets current or historical code requirements and a licensed certifier inspects them.</p>

      <p>A non-compliant structure is one that does not meet the relevant building code or local planning requirements, regardless of whether it was approved or not. A structure might have been approved at the time it was built under a standard that no longer applies, or it might have been modified since approval in ways that introduced non-compliance. Non-compliant structures are more difficult and sometimes impossible to retrospectively approve. In some cases they may need to be removed or substantially rebuilt to achieve compliance.</p>

      <p>Before you decide how to handle an unapproved structure, it is worth getting a preliminary assessment from a licensed building certifier about whether the structure is likely to be approvable. This is usually a relatively low-cost exercise and gives you a clear picture of your options before you commit to a course of action.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Your disclosure obligations as a seller in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Queensland law is clear that sellers must disclose known material facts about a property that a buyer could reasonably be expected to want to know before deciding to purchase. Unapproved structures fall squarely within this obligation. If you know that the deck at the back of the house was built without a permit, you are required to disclose that in the seller's disclosure statement or as a special condition of the contract. Failing to disclose a known unapproved structure that is later discovered by the buyer can expose you to claims for damages or, in serious cases, rescission of the contract.</p>

      <p>The obligation is to disclose what you know. If you genuinely did not know that a structure was unapproved because you purchased the property with it already in place and it was not flagged at your own purchase, your exposure is reduced. But once you are aware of the issue, whether through a pre-sale inspection, a council records search, or your own knowledge of work that was done, the disclosure obligation is engaged.</p>

      <p>Your conveyancer should review the seller's disclosure statement carefully and ensure any known unapproved structures are accurately described. Do not leave this to the last minute before signing the contract. Work through it before you go to market so that the contract documents are accurate from the moment the property is listed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to get retrospective approval</h2>
      <p>Retrospective approval, sometimes called a building approval for existing work, is the formal process of submitting an unapproved structure for assessment after it has already been built. In Queensland, this is done through a licensed private certifier or, in some cases, directly through Brisbane City Council. The process involves the certifier inspecting the structure against the relevant building code requirements that apply, preparing documentation, and issuing an approval if the work meets the standard.</p>

      <p>For structures that are straightforwardly approvable, the process can typically be completed within a few weeks and at relatively modest cost, often $1,500 to $4,000 depending on the size and complexity of the structure. For more complex cases, particularly where the structure borders a boundary setback, has structural questions, or involves a secondary dwelling with specific amenity requirements, the process takes longer and may require additional work to bring the structure into compliance before approval is granted.</p>

      <p>Getting retrospective approval before selling removes the issue from the disclosure statement entirely and avoids any buyer discount for the risk. For structures that are clearly approvable, it is almost always worth completing before going to market rather than leaving it for the buyer to deal with.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Impact on sale price and buyer finance</h2>
      <p>Unapproved structures affect buyer confidence in ways that go beyond the direct cost of approval. Buyers and their conveyancers treat unapproved structures as unknowns: they do not know if the structure is approvable, what it would cost to remedy, or whether it might need to be removed entirely. In the absence of that certainty, buyers discount.</p>

      <p>The discount varies considerably depending on the structure and the market. An unapproved garden shed represents negligible risk and is unlikely to affect price. An unapproved secondary dwelling that the vendor has been marketing as a key feature of the property, and that turns out to require significant remediation to achieve approval, represents meaningful risk and will be reflected in offers.</p>

      <p>Buyer finance is also a consideration. Lenders assess security value, and some will not lend against properties with unapproved structures above a certain size or value contribution to the property. An unapproved secondary dwelling being counted toward the effective yield of an investment property is a situation where a lender's valuer may flag the approval status and require resolution before unconditional finance is granted. This can cause contracts to fall over during the finance condition period even where the buyer is otherwise willing to proceed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if unapproved work is discovered after settlement?</h2>
      <p>If a buyer discovers an unapproved structure after settlement that the seller knew about and did not disclose, the buyer's remedies depend on the circumstances. In straightforward cases where the non-disclosure is clear and the cost of remediation is quantifiable, the buyer may pursue damages through the Queensland Civil and Administrative Tribunal or the courts for the cost of bringing the structure into compliance or removing it.</p>

      <p>Where the non-disclosure was serious enough to constitute misrepresentation, and where the buyer can demonstrate they would not have proceeded on the same terms had they known about the issue, they may have a case for more significant remedies. Post-settlement disputes over unapproved structures are not uncommon and they are almost always more expensive and more stressful than dealing with the issue transparently before the sale.</p>

      <p>The principle is simple: disclose what you know, get retrospective approval where it is practical, and do not treat an as-is clause or a carefully worded contract as a substitute for transparency. Your conveyancer and your agent should both be across the issue before contracts are exchanged.</p>

